      "content": "Sure, here's a simplified script to get you started:\n\n```python\n# Dependencies\nimport spacy\n\n# Load an English model for spaCy\nnlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')\n\n# Your function\ndef dependency_parse(sentence):\n    parsed = nlp(sentence)\n    return [(x.head.text, x.text) for x in parsed]\n\n# Testing function\ndef test_dependency_parse():\n    sentence = \"the patient shows signs of acute respiratory distress\"\n    expected_deps = [(\"shows\", \"patient\"), (\"shows\", \"signs\"), (\"signs\", \"of\"), (\"of\", \"distress\"), (\"distress\", \"respiratory\"), (\"respiratory\", \"acute\")]\n    \n    actual_deps = dependency_parse(sentence)\n    \n    assert sorted(actual_deps) == sorted(expected_deps), f\"Test failed. Got {actual_deps}, expected {expected_deps}\"\n    \n    print(\"Dependency parse test passed.\")\n\n# Run test\ntest_dependency_parse()\n```\n\nThe script uses the `spaCy` library, which provides pre-trained models that include a dependency parser. You need to install it via pip (`pip install spacy`) and download the English model (`python -m spacy",
